{"type":"message","id":"de24cd04","parentId":"0fe12076","timestamp":"2026-03-24T16:18:34.930Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_p38r26dpcmdz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"﻿# Pulse: 2026-03-24 121716\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine a concrete action that advances the goals.\r\n\r\nCurrent state:\r\n- Phase 0 and Phase 1 are complete\r\n- CFI analysis is done (44.8% pure noise, 5.7% true causal anchors)\r\n- Next pending action: CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nThe most logical next step is to implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment. This involves comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nI should create an experiment script or documentation that:\r\n1. Defines the methodology for comparing CFI-weighted vs frequency baseline\r\n2. Sets up the test framework\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete action - either an experiment spec or the actual compression comparison script.\r\n\r\nI'll create a specification for the CFI-weighted compression experiment in the research directory.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nCFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise (CFI=0). This suggests frequency-based compression loses signal while CFI-weighted compression should preserve causal structure. The next step is a direct comparison.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the CFI-weighted compression experiment specification with methodology for comparing CFI vs frequency baseline on next-pulse prediction quality.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** Pending execution\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression preserves causal predictive power better than frequency-only compression. The experiment measures whether invariants with high CFI (>=0.7) are better predictors of next-pulse content than high-frequency invariants.\r\n\r\n## Methodology\r\n\r\n### Baseline (Frequency-Only)\r\n1. Extract all text invariants from pulse history\r\n2. Rank by frequency descending\r\n3. Compress to top-N tokens using frequency\r\n4. Predict next-pulse content from compressed state\r\n\r\n### CFI-Weighted\r\n1. Extract all text invariants with CFI scores\r\n2. Filter to CFI >= 0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n3. Rank remaining by CFI * log(frequency)\r\n4. Compress to same top-N tokens\r\n5. Predict next-pulse content from compressed state\r\n\r\n### Metrics\r\n- **Prediction accuracy:** % of key terms in pulse N+1 correctly predicted from pulse N's compressed state\r\n- **Signal retention:** ratio of causal terms preserved vs baseline\r\n- **Noise rejection:** % of noise (CFI=0 invariants) in compressed state\r\n\r\n## Test Data\r\n- Pulse history: `state/pulse_*.md`\r\n- CFI scores: `research/CFI_RESULTS.md`\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-weighted compression should show higher prediction accuracy despite potentially using fewer tokens, confirming that high-CFI invariants are true causal anchors.\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 12:17:31\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774369114928}}
